{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533055"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14735"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.12,0.1,0.71,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112964"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7428"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94997"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45756"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112964"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for preoperative assessment before an elective inguinal hernia repair. He had an ST-elevation myocardial infarction six weeks ago, treated with primary percutaneous coronary intervention and drug-eluting stent placement. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include aspirin, ticagrelor, metoprolol, ramipril, atorvastatin, and metformin. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His surgical hernia is reducible and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proceed with surgery under local anaesthetic","Stop antiplatelet therapy to proceed to surgery","Delay surgery for four weeks","Delay surgery for six weeks","Proceed with surgery next week"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents for preoperative assessment six weeks after a myocardial infarction (MI) requiring stenting. The timing of non-cardiac surgery after MI is crucial for minimising perioperative cardiac complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelay surgery for six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option. As the patient has presented isx weeks after MI, a further six week waiting period would place the patient\u0027s surgery at the three-month mark. Current guidelines recommend postponing elective non-cardiac surgery for at least three months after MI, as this period carries the highest risk of perioperative cardiac events. This delay allows for cardiac recovery, stabilisation of coronary plaques, and completion of crucial dual antiplatelet therapy. Depending on the patient\u0027s co-morbidities, the delays may be even longer than three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed with surgery next week\u003C/strong\u003E would expose the patient to unnecessary risk of perioperative cardiac complications, given the recent MI. The risk of reinfarction, heart failure, and death is highest within the first three months post-MI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStop antiplatelet therapy to proceed to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous as premature discontinuation of dual antiplatelet therapy increases the risk of stent thrombosis, particularly with recent drug-eluting stent placement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelay surgery for four weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient time after a recent MI. The risk of major adverse cardiac events remains significantly elevated until at least three months post-MI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed with surgery under local anaesthetic\u003C/strong\u003E would not mitigate the underlying cardiac risk. The type of anaesthesia does not significantly alter the risk of cardiac complications in the early post-MI period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe inguinal hernia in this case is reducible and non-tender, indicating it is not incarcerated or strangulated. It is suitable for a planned elective procedure. Therefore, delaying surgery for three months is safe and appropriate. During this time, the patient should continue all cardiac medications, including dual antiplatelet therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-urgent surgery should be delayed for at least 3 months following a myocardial infarction to reduce perioperative cardiac complications.","Risk factors for perioperative cardiac events include recent myocardial infarction, heart failure, and complex surgery.","The risk of major adverse cardiac events is highest within 3 months of myocardial infarction."],"references":["2024 AHA/ACC/ACS/ASNC/HRS/ SCA/SCCT/SCMR/SVM Guideline for Perioperative Cardiovascular Management for Noncardiac Surgery","Glance LG, Joynt Maddox KE, Thomas S, et al. Time Since Prior NSTEMI and Major Adverse Cardiovascular and Cerebrovascular Events After Noncardiac Surgery. JAMA Surg. 2025; 160:45-54."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94997"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94997"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T17:19:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T17:19:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7428"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112964"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4953"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cardiovascular Health","synonyms":null,"descript